#If and Else Statements

```py
if ctx.guild.id == id: #ints stay out of quotes, while strings go in quotes
  return True
else:
  return False```
 
So that is a basic statement. If the guild id == the id you provide it will return True and run
Otherwise (else) it will return false

You can do the same thing with this:
```py
if ctx.author.id in ctx.bot.owner_ids: #you could use the @commands.is_owner check tbh
  do stuff
else
  return await ctx.reply("You must be an owner to use this command")```
  
The if/else statements can go on and on forever.

If you want a command to behave differently depending on the circumstances, you can use elif (elseif)

```py
if ctx.guild.id == id:
  await ctx.send("Is main guild"):
elif ctx.guild.id == id2: #You must have a statement when using elif
  await ctx.send("Is secondary guild")
else:
  await ctx.send("Is neither main or secondary guild")
